Google=E2=80=99s Apple Payments
-----------------------

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-11-13/apple-g=
ets-36-of-google-revenue-from-search-deal-witness-says ) :

Google pays Apple Inc. 36% of the revenue it earns from search advertising =
made through the Safari browser, the main economics expert for the Alphabet=
 Inc. unit said Monday. Kevin Murphy, a University of Chicago professor, di=
sclosed the number during his testimony in Google=E2=80=99s defense at the =
Justice Department=E2=80=99s antitrust trial in Washington. John Schmidtlei=
n, Google=E2=80=99s main litigator, visibly cringed when Murphy said the nu=
mber, which was supposed to remain confidential.

This is, needless to say, a particularly juicy bit of information; it=E2=80=
=99s also interesting to consider in light of this New York Times report ( =
https://www.nytimes.com/2023/10/26/technology/google-apple-search-spotlight=
.html ) late last month that Google paid Apple $18 billion in 2021.

To put these numbers in context:

* $18 billion in payments to Apple implies total Safari revenue for Google =
of $50 billion.
* Google earned $178 billion in advertising revenue on Google Sites in 2021=
, which means that Safari drives around 28% of Google=E2=80=99s Sites reven=
ue.
* Google paid $46 billion in traffic acquisition costs (TAC) in 2021, of wh=
ich Apple captured 39%.

Start with that 28% number: that is actually pretty closely in line with bo=
th Safari=E2=80=99s marketshare of 27% and iOS=E2=80=99s marketshare of 30%=
. I think, though, that is more of a coincidence than anything: iPhone user=
s are famously more affluent, which may make their searches worth more, and=
 the iPhone has much higher marketshare in the U.S., which commands the hig=
hest advertising rates. Both factors would suggest that Safari=E2=80=99s re=
venue share of Google Sites revenue should be higher.

I suspect the reason it is not is that Safari=E2=80=99s share is predominan=
tly iPhone, and that mobile probably still monetizes at a lower rate than d=
esktop, which makes sense: some of the most valuable keywords, like those a=
ssociated with travel or insurance are probably entered when users are in =
=E2=80=9Cresearch mode=E2=80=9D, i.e. much more likely to be using a comput=
er, relatively speaking.

What is more interesting is the disparity between Safari=E2=80=99s share of=
 revenue and Apple=E2=80=99s share of TAC. At first glance, this disparity =
might seem to be due to the aforementioned affluent customers, which would =
be worth more to Google. Remember, though, that this deal is a revenue shar=
e, not a payment: the affluence premium is already included in the numbers.=
 Apple is getting that number by having a superior negotiating position rel=
atively speaking.

Here affluent customers do matter: losing an Apple customer to another defa=
ult hurts Google more than losing another Samsung customer or Firefox custo=
mer or whoever else, so Apple can press for a higher rate.

Second, while iOS may only have 30% of the global market and around 50% of =
the U.S. market, all of iOS is controlled by and negotiated for by Apple; A=
ndroid, on the other hand, is split up amongst a host of manufacturers. Thi=
s gives Apple further leverage because losing them affects more phones than=
 anyone else.

Third, while any manufacturer can play Google off of Microsoft, Apple is th=
e only phone maker that has a credible threat of building their own alterna=
tive search engine, and the theoretical motivation to do so (their privacy =
stance). This also seems to be what Google is more worried about than anyth=
ing. From the aforelinked New York Times article:

For years, Google watched with increasing concern as Apple improved its sea=
rch technology, not knowing whether its longtime partner and sometimes comp=
etitor would eventually build its own search engine. Those fears ratcheted =
up in 2021, when Google paid Apple around $18 billion to keep Google=E2=80=
=99s search engine the default selection on iPhones, according to two peopl=
e with knowledge of the partnership, who were not authorized to discuss it =
publicly. The same year, Apple=E2=80=99s iPhone search tool, Spotlight, beg=
an showing users richer web results like those they could have found on Goo=
gle=E2=80=A6

Google was concerned about Apple=E2=80=99s Spotlight from the feature=E2=80=
=99s earliest days. In 2014, an internal presentation discussed the impact =
that Apple=E2=80=99s new operating system, iOS 8, could have on Google=E2=
=80=99s revenue. The second page of the slide deck was titled =E2=80=9CBott=
om Line: It=E2=80=99s bad,=E2=80=9D according to a presentation ( https://w=
ww.justice.gov/d9/2023-10/417005.pdf ) introduced as evidence in the antitr=
ust trial. =E2=80=9CWe expect these suggestions to siphon queries away from=
 Google in verticals where Spotlight is triggered,=E2=80=9D the company wro=
te.

Apple poached ( https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/03/business/apple-hires-goo=
gles-ai-chief.html ) a powerful Google search executive, John Giannandrea, =
in 2018, and expanded its teams of search employees as it built a more capa=
ble Spotlight system. The 2021 improvements to the tool, as part of iOS 15,=
 sparked concerns at Google over Apple=E2=80=99s intentions in the search m=
arket, a person with knowledge of the discussions said=E2=80=A6In recent ye=
ars, Apple has not used Spotlight to crib so-called commercial queries =E2=
=80=94 which feature ads in their results =E2=80=94 from Google, so the too=
l has not hurt Google=E2=80=99s search business.

It certainly has not hurt Apple=E2=80=99s business either. To add some more=
 numbers for context, in 2021 Apple=E2=80=99s Services business did $72 bil=
lion in revenue, and had $21 billion in costs, for a net profit of $51 bill=
ion and a net margin of 71%. The Google deal, though, is pure profit: $18 b=
illion in revenue is $18 billion in profit; if you took away the Google dea=
l then Apple=E2=80=99s Services would have had 2021 revenue of $54 billion,=
 the same $21 billion in costs, for a net profit of $33 billion and a net m=
argin of 61%.

Apple Services: Narrative vs. Reality
-------------------------------------

Of course in this scenario Apple=E2=80=99s costs might not be so significan=
t; Apple TV+ in particular reminds of an observation Peter Thiel made in Ze=
ro to One ( https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/234730/zero-to-one-by-=
peter-thiel-with-blake-masters/ ) :

Monopolists lie to protect themselves. They know that bragging about their =
great monopoly invites being audited, scrutinized, and attacked. Since they=
 very much want their monopoly profits to continue unmolested, they tend to=
 do whatever they can to conceal their monopoly =E2=80=94 usually by exagge=
rating the power of their (nonexistent) competition.

Think about how Google talks about its business. It certainly doesn=E2=80=
=99t claim to be a monopoly. But is it one? Well, it depends: a monopoly in=
 what? Let=E2=80=99s say that Google is primarily a search engine. As of Ma=
y 2014, it owns about 68% of the search market=E2=80=A6But suppose we say t=
hat Google is primarily an advertising company. That changes things=E2=80=
=A6global advertising is a $495 billion market. So even if Google completel=
y monopolized U.S. search engine advertising, it would own just 3.4% of the=
 global advertising market. From this angle, Google looks like a small play=
er in a competitive world.

What if we frame Google as a multifaceted technology company instead? This =
seems reasonable enough; in addition to its search engine, Google makes doz=
ens of other software products, not to mention robotic cars, Android phones=
, and wearable computers. But 95% of Google=E2=80=99s revenue comes from se=
arch advertising; its other products generated just $2.35 billion in 2012, =
and its consumer tech products a mere fraction of that. Since consumer tech=
 is a $964 billion market globally, Google owns less than 0.24% of it =E2=
=80=94 a far cry from relevance, let alone monopoly. Framing itself as just=
 another tech company allows Google to escape all sorts of unwanted attenti=
on.

In the case of Apple and services, notice how CEO Tim Cook talked about the=
 division that is an increasingly essential driver of Apple=E2=80=99s growt=
h on the company=E2=80=99s most recent earnings call ( https://seekingalpha=
.com/article/4646927-apple-inc-aapl-q4-2023-earnings-call-transcript ) :

Services revenue set an all-time record of $22.3 billion, a 16% year-over-y=
ear increase. We achieved all-time revenue records across App Store, advert=
ising, AppleCare, iCloud, payment services, and video, as well as the Septe=
mber quarter revenue record in Apple Music. Whether subscribers are waking =
up to headlines on Apple News+, getting their morning workout in with Fitne=
ss+, feeling the beat with Apple Music on their way to work or school, or u=
nwinding at the end of the day with Apple Arcade, we have so many different=
 services to enrich their day.

Apple TV+ continues to delight customers as well, with new and returning sh=
ows like the Morning Show, Lessons in Chemistry and Monarch. We=E2=80=99re =
telling impactful stories that inspire imagination and stir the soul. Makin=
g movies that make a difference is also at the heart of Apple TV+ and we we=
re thrilled to produce Martin Scorsese=E2=80=99s Killers of the Flower Moon=
, a powerful work of cinema that premiered in theaters around the world las=
t month. We=E2=80=99re proud to say that since launch, just over four years=
 ago, Apple TV+ has earned nearly 1,600 award nominations and nearly 400 wi=
ns.

We also offer subscribers an unprecedented live sports experience with MLS =
Season Pass. We couldn=E2=80=99t be more pleased with how our partnership w=
ith Major League Soccer has gone in its first year. Subscriptions to MLS Se=
ason Pass have exceeded our expectations and we=E2=80=99re excited to conti=
nue that momentum next year. With the playoffs now underway, we can=E2=80=
=99t wait to see who takes home MLS cup.

It=E2=80=99s not just that there is no mention of revenue from Google (of c=
ourse not); there is barely a mention of the App Store, as well. What there=
 is are two paragraphs about video content that has very little strategic i=
mport but costs a fair bit of money and is something very visible to consum=
ers and regulators; I imagine it=E2=80=99s one of the first things people t=
hink of when they hear =E2=80=9CApple Services=E2=80=9D, and I think that=
=E2=80=99s the point. And, by extension, if Apple didn=E2=80=99t have reven=
ue to distract from, it might not feel the need to spend so much on said di=
stractions.

