Google=E2=80=99s Motivation
-------------------

That last section was actually the fourth reason why Apple has such strong =
negotiating leverage versus Google: Google in many respects wants to give A=
pple so much money. When this deal was first signed two decades ago it was =
a sprinkle on the Apple profit cake; today, though, it is a huge chunk of t=
he cake. In other words, it is almost impossible to imagine Apple ever givi=
ng up this revenue, which is to say it is almost impossible to imagine Appl=
e building its own competitive search engine.

The reason why Google even feared this in the first place goes back to Appl=
e Maps; from Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-09-20=
/google-antitrust-trial-google-lost-map-traffic-with-apple-s-iphone-switch =
) in September:

Two years after Apple Inc. dropped Google Maps as its default service on iP=
hones in favor of its own app, Google had regained only 40% of the mobile t=
raffic it used to have on its mapping service, a Google executive testified=
 in the antitrust trial against the Alphabet Inc. company. Michael Roszak, =
Google=E2=80=99s vice president for finance, said Tuesday that the company =
used the Apple Maps switch as =E2=80=9Ca data point=E2=80=9D when modeling =
what might happen if the iPhone maker replaced Google=E2=80=99s search engi=
ne as the default on Apple=E2=80=99s Safari browser.

I=E2=80=99ve written about how Google screwed up Google Maps on iOS previou=
sly: by prioritizing Android with turn-by-turn directions and trying to squ=
eeze more data from Apple, Google gave the impetus for Apple to build an al=
ternative. And, it should be noted, when Apple Maps launched it was better =
than Google Maps because it had turn-by-turn directions, even if the maps w=
ere worse; Google finally added turn-by-turn directions to Google Maps shor=
tly thereafter, but the damage had been done: for enough users Apple Maps w=
as good enough, and over time the gap between the two services has shrunk s=
ignificantly.

The loss of Google Maps data was certainly a big blow to Google; the loss o=
f Google as default would be a much more significant one. Yes, Google searc=
h would be =E2=80=9Cbetter=E2=80=9D, and I suspect that many more people wo=
uld change the default for Search than go to the effort of downloading and =
opening a different app when they wanted to drive somewhere; not only do pe=
ople search more than they use maps, but it=E2=80=99s also something you on=
ly need to change once. Why risk it, though? By forgoing 36% of revenue Goo=
gle has foreclosed competition from its biggest threat basically permanentl=
y.

This does raise a question I get frequently: how can I argue that Google wi=
ns by being better when it is willing to pay for default status? I articula=
ted the answer on a recent episode of Sharp Tech ( https://sharptech.fm/mem=
ber/episode/googles-calculus-with-mobile-search-what-us-v-google-makes-clea=
r-about-apple-two-types-of-regulation ) , but briefly, nothing exists in a =
vacuum: defaults do matter, and that absolutely impacts how much better you=
 have to be to force a switch. In this case Google took the possibility off=
 of the table completely, and it was a pretty rational decision in my mind.

It also, without question, reduced competition in the space, which is why I=
